

The numbers are placed on a hexagonal (pointy‑top) lattice in a spiral.
The centre is  

\[
1\;(0,0)
\]

and the six directions (in axial coordinates) are  

\[
E=(1,0),\; NE=(0,-1),\; NW=(-1,-1),\; W=(-1,0),\; SW=(0,1),\; SE=(1,1).
\]

For a cell at a distance \(r\) from the centre (the “ring’’) there are  

\[
N(r)=1+3r(r+1)
\]

cells up to that ring.  
Ring \(r\) starts at the cell \((r,0)\) with number \(N(r-1)+1\) and proceeds
around the ring in the order  

\[
NW,\;W,\;SW,\;SE,\;E,\;NE .
\]

The side lengths are \(r\); the last side (\(NE\)) contains only \(r-1\) new
cells, because the \(r\)‑th step would return to the start of the ring.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  locating the number 2026  

\(2026\) lies in ring \(r\) with  

\[
N(r-1)<2026\le N(r).
\]

Since  

\[
N(25)=1+3\cdot25\cdot26=1951,\qquad
N(26)=1+3\cdot26\cdot27=2107,
\]

we have \(r=26\).  
The offset within the ring is  

\[
k=2026-N(25)=2026-1951=75 .
\]

The ring of radius \(26\) consists of six blocks of length \(r\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
&[2,27]      &&\text{(NW)}\\
&[28,53]     &&\text{(W)}\\
&[54,79]     &&\text{(SW)}\\
&[80,105]    &&\text{(SE)}\\
&[106,131]   &&\text{(E)}\\
&[132,156]   &&\text{(NE)} .
\end{aligned}
\]

Because \(75\in[54,79]\), the cell is on the **SW** side.  
On the SW side the coordinates are \((-r,\,-r+i)\) with
\(i=k-(2r+1)\).  Here  

\[
i=75-(2\cdot26+1)=22 .
\]

Hence the axial coordinates of 2026 are  

\[
(-26,\,-4).
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  the six neighbours  

Adding the six neighbour vectors gives the neighbour coordinates:

\[
\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{direction} & \text{coord.},\;d  \\ \hline
E & (-25,-4),\;25\\
NE& (-26,-5),\;26\\
NW& (-27,-5),\;27\\
W & (-27,-4),\;27\\
SW& (-26,-3),\;26\\
SE& (-25,-3),\;25
\end{array}
\]

The distance \(d\) (the ring number) is computed by  

\[
d=\max(|q|,\;|r|,\;|q-r|).
\]

Thus two neighbours lie in ring 25, two in ring 26 and two in ring 27.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  numbers on those coordinates  

For a cell in ring \(r\) with offset \(s\) (the \(s\)-th cell of that ring,
starting with \(s=0\) at \((r,0)\))

\[
\text{number}=N(r-1)+1+s .
\]

**Ring 25** (starts at 1802)

* \((-25,-4)\) – SW side, \(k=71\) → \(1802+71 = 1873\)
* \((-25,-3)\) – SW side, \(k=72\) → \(1802+72 = 1874\)

**Ring 26** (starts at 1952)

* \((-26,-5)\) – SW side, \(k=73\) → \(1952+73 = 2025\)
* \((-26,-3)\) – SW side, \(k=75\) → \(1952+75 = 2027\)

**Ring 27** (starts at 2108)

* \((-27,-5)\) – SW side, \(k=76\) → \(2108+76 = 2184\)
* \((-27,-4)\) – SW side, \(k=77\) → \(2108+77 = 2185\)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.  sum of the six neighbours  

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sum &=1873+1874+2025+2027+2184+2185\\
     &= (1873+1874)+(2025+2027)+(2184+2185)\\
     &= 3747+4052+4369\\
     &= 12168 .
\end{aligned}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------
\[
\boxed{12168}
\]
